1.	Inventory Committee to – 

a.Conduct the annual physical inventory of PPEs under the name of the LGU and relieve each member, or their representatives, of their regular functions to devote themselves in completing the same;

b.Prepare the PIP, and submit the same to the Municipal Mayor to ensure that the conduct of inventory taking is properly and adequately planned pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;

c.Submit a copy of the approved PIP to COA at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities;

d.Use pre-numbered property stickers bearing the vital information on the PPE items, such as

a)	Description of the Property
b)	Model Number
c)	Serial Number
d)	Acquisition Date / Cost
e)	Person Accountable
f)	Space for the Validation / Signature of Inventory Committee

In the conduct of physical inventory and attach the same to the prominent and secured portion of the inventoried PPE for proper and easy identification;

2.Municipal Treasurer as the Designated Municipal General Services Officer to – 

a.Use pre-numbered property tags or control stickers to all PPE containing the information required under Section 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 and attach the same to the prominent and secured portion of the inventoried PPE for proper and easy identification;

b.Ensure that all issuances of PPE items are covered with PARs as prescribed under Section 5.6 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; and

c.Renew/Update issued PARs every three (3) years after issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship to establish proper accountability.

To strengthen the risk management capabilities of the Municipal Government of Sibutad and enable it to manage its vulnerabilities in the event of disruptive events, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

a. to conduct risk assessment;
b. to identify critical processes and functions;
c. to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operations;
d. to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
e. to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
f. to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a Resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of the PSCP.

We recommended that Management require the BAC to:

Establish procurement timelines in the APP that is a product of judicious planning and prioritization to serve as a guiding and monitoring tool in the procurement activities and in consonance with PPA schedules and PPA implementations for each calendar year;

Ensure that specific cut-offs shall be provided from the preparation and submission of the Purchase Request, the posting of the same in the PhilGEPS, conduct of the Bidding activities, and some other processes necessary for tye procurement required in RA No. 9184 to avoid and/or minimize the delays incurred in the procurement transactions of the LGU;

Monitor the delivery of goods to the awarded suppliers and impose liquidated damages at least one-tenth (1/10) of one per cent (1%) of the cost of the delayed goods scheduled for delivery for every day of delay until such goods are finally delivered and accepted by the procuring entity; and

Ensure that proper documentation be provided to the Accounting Unit, as the designated internal audit of the agency so as to pay the suppliers on time of the amounts due to them, and to encourage other legitimate suppliers to bid for other procurement activities since the LGU pays promptly. This would result in the attainment of the procurement of the best quality of goods and services at the most reasonable price.

Require the Municipal Engineer to submit weather bulletin from the PAGASA to the Resident Auditors instead of the manually prepared weather chart to justify the Suspension Orders issued for the frequency of rains;

For the absence of valid proof in the issuance of suspension orders, require the Municipal Accountant to compute and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth (1/10) of one percent (1%) of the cost of the unperformed portion of every day of delay; and

Require the contractor to complete the projects as soon as possible.

Recommendations:
